description: From Middle English pawe, from Old French poue, poe, from Frankish *pōta (compare Dutch poot, Low German Pote, German Pfote), from Frankish *pōtōn (“to put, stick, plant”) (compare Dutch poten 'to plant'), from Proto-Germanic *putōną (compare Old English potian (“to push”), pȳtan (“to put out, poke out”), Icelandic pota (“to stick”), Albanian putër 'paw'). More at put.

entries.meaning: The soft foot of a mammal or other animal, generally a quadruped, that has claws or nails; comparable to a human hand or foot.

examples: Get your grubby paws off my things!

verbs.description: paw (third-person singular simple present paws, present participle pawing, simple past and past participle pawed)

entries.meaning: (of an animal) To go through something (such as a garbage can) with paws.
(of an animal) To gently push on something with a paw.
(of an animal) To draw the forefoot along the ground; to beat or scrape with the forefoot.
examples: He paweth in the valley, and rejoiceth in his strength: he goeth on to meet the armed men.

entries.meaning: (by extension) To touch someone in a sexual way.
examples: IronMan used to be good in this way, back in the '80s.  […]  They wouldn't subscribe to the old, "Let's put a male bodybuilder with silicone babes pawing him" cover that's mainstay now.

entries.meaning: (by extension) To clumsily dig through something.

description: The word probably has an origin in baby talk: see ‘pa’.

examples: Synonyms: pawpaw, pa, papa, father, dad, daddy, pappy
Coordinate terms: maw, brother, sis, sissy
